b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48496.htm)  [Next](sbe48498.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n51\\. In the same way there is non-determination with regard to what has\nRelease for its result; that condition being ascertained, that condition being\nascertained.\n\nSo likewise in the case of the origination, through works of very great merit,\nof such knowledge as has for its result final Release, the time is not\ndefinitely fixed; for here also there is ascertained the same condition, viz.\nthe termination of the obstruction presented by other works. A further doubt\nmight in this case be raised on the ground that such works as give rise to\nknowledge leading to final Release are stronger than all other works, and\ntherefore not\n\np. 714\n\nliable to obstruction. But this doubt is disposed of by the reflection that\neven in the case of a man knowing Brahman there may exist previous evil deeds\nof overpowering strength.--The repetition of the last words of the Sutra\nindicates the completion of the adhyaya.--Here terminates the adhikara _n_ a\nof 'what has Release for its result.'\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: First Pada: 1. Repetition...](sbe48498.htm)\n\n"